50
00:03:39,623 --> 00:03:41,184
with the content and context.

51
00:03:41,925 --> 00:03:45,007
It's a skill that will improve with experience.

52
00:03:45,047 --> 00:03:46,468
The more you do it, the better you get.

53
00:03:46,548 --> 00:03:48,930
So, ask yourself, how does the type feel?

54
00:03:49,731 --> 00:03:53,074
Is it slow, is it fast, is it light, is it heavy?

55
00:03:55,640 --> 00:03:57,922
Think about the images that will accompany the text,

56
00:03:57,962 --> 00:04:03,106
or the objects, or places, time periods, or attitudes.

57
00:04:04,967 --> 00:04:07,449
What typefaces would your characters use

58
00:04:07,729 --> 00:04:08,610
if they had to choose?

59
00:04:10,375 --> 00:04:17,522
In a game like Far Cry 3, the distress and static of the type describes the insanity

60
00:04:18,003 --> 00:04:20,085
and the instability of the antagonist.

61
00:04:20,705 --> 00:04:25,930
And they use quotes from Alice in Wonderland as a metaphor for his descent into madness.

62
00:04:26,971 --> 00:04:29,533
So we have this gritty, broken world that you're in.

63
00:04:30,756 --> 00:04:33,358
And if you notice, there's a little icon in the corner there

64
00:04:33,398 --> 00:04:36,359
of, like, a mirror image of guns.

65
00:04:36,379 --> 00:04:37,920
It looks like a butterfly.

66
00:04:38,761 --> 00:04:42,863
And so that fits with this tropical island world

67
00:04:42,883 --> 00:04:46,246
that they're in, and they use this as a design element

68
00:04:46,826 --> 00:04:47,406
throughout the game.

69
00:04:47,466 --> 00:04:49,888
They have a mirror image of the guns here,

70
00:04:50,388 --> 00:04:52,770
or even how they treat the type, too.

71
00:04:53,450 --> 00:04:56,332
So they have the type mirrored from the center.

72
00:04:57,332 --> 00:04:57,492
And...

73
00:04:58,611 --> 00:05:00,112
I thought that was just a really good,

74
00:05:01,692 --> 00:05:03,653
just a really good repeating design element.

75
00:05:05,834 --> 00:05:08,335
Perhaps you have a story like Battlestar Galactica.

76
00:05:09,976 --> 00:05:11,797
You have this type style that's futuristic.

77
00:05:12,137 --> 00:05:14,538
A geometric sans serif is almost a given

78
00:05:15,238 --> 00:05:16,459
for the side of a spaceship.

79
00:05:17,299 --> 00:05:19,500
But the people in the story are also

80
00:05:19,560 --> 00:05:22,261
greatly influenced by tradition and antiquity,

81
00:05:22,862 --> 00:05:23,902
or Greek mythology.

82
00:05:25,537 --> 00:05:30,062
So here, they're using the shape of a Greek delta for the A,

83
00:05:30,983 --> 00:05:31,884
which is a nice twist.

84
00:05:32,625 --> 00:05:34,086
So maybe the people in the story

85
00:05:34,166 --> 00:05:35,848
are so influenced by ancient Greece

86
00:05:36,369 --> 00:05:39,453
that they incorporate the Greek alphabet somehow.

87
00:05:40,293 --> 00:05:43,417
And I think a detail like this can add a richness

88
00:05:43,497 --> 00:05:45,760
to the story and the experience of the game.

89
00:05:46,546 --> 00:05:49,308
Your 12-year-old player will still be able to read it,

90
00:05:49,788 --> 00:05:53,751
but your, you know, 30-year-old college graduate player

91
00:05:53,911 --> 00:05:56,152
is going to delight in the detail.

92
00:05:58,314 --> 00:06:01,556
So classifications and time periods

93
00:06:01,776 --> 00:06:05,118
are origin points that help us describe an organized type.

94
00:06:05,539 --> 00:06:08,241
These are genres of typefaces.

95
00:06:09,321 --> 00:06:11,203
But they're also not cut and dry.

96
00:06:11,523 --> 00:06:13,824
So there's a lot of exceptions and overlaps.

97
00:06:15,501 --> 00:06:18,162
just like music or video games.

98
00:06:21,223 --> 00:06:23,243
Knowing the main genres and descriptors

99
00:06:23,303 --> 00:06:27,284
can help you choose fonts by giving you a starting point.

100
00:06:29,065 --> 00:06:31,726
And there are a lot of books and resources

101
00:06:31,786 --> 00:06:35,206
on the topic and stuff. I have some recommended resources

102
00:06:35,266 --> 00:06:39,288
on my blog, too, if you look it up. But just like games and music,

103
00:06:39,328 --> 00:06:42,048
there's exciting things that happen in between the genres.

104
00:06:44,231 --> 00:06:46,452
Of course, there's a rich history to type,

105
00:06:47,092 --> 00:06:50,714
and even long before Gutenberg and the first printed books,

106
00:06:52,014 --> 00:06:55,796
organizing type as we know it today with paragraphs and punctuation,

107
00:06:56,096 --> 00:06:59,818
you know, developed over hundreds of years with calligraphy and manuscripts.

108
00:07:00,558 --> 00:07:04,640
And those traditions were, you know, soaked in into printing.

109
00:07:05,841 --> 00:07:07,161
That's what people were used to reading.

110
00:07:08,661 --> 00:07:11,583
There's actually a game that will teach you about typographic history.

111
00:07:13,224 --> 00:07:15,226
And while you play it, it's called Typewriter.

112
00:07:16,167 --> 00:07:20,671
And it's a platformer where you're using a little bit of punctuation,

113
00:07:20,891 --> 00:07:22,573
like a car colon.

114
00:07:23,073 --> 00:07:27,034
thing, and you run and jump through puzzles and props

115
00:07:27,134 --> 00:07:31,455
in this typographic and pretty historically accurate world.

116
00:07:31,756 --> 00:07:34,056
A little European modernism here.

117
00:07:36,057 --> 00:07:36,517
Pretty sweet.

118
00:07:37,997 --> 00:07:41,479
I don't have enough time to go into all of the genres

119
00:07:41,519 --> 00:07:43,899
and stuff in depth today, but I wanted to zoom in on a few.

120
00:07:46,435 --> 00:07:50,199
So, back in the day, this style was called grotesque in Europe,

121
00:07:50,499 --> 00:07:52,261
and gothic in the Americas.

122
00:07:53,242 --> 00:07:57,326
And, they have, like Helvetica, and trade gothic, for example.

123
00:07:58,166 --> 00:08:01,530
And there are some differentiators between a grotesque and a gothic,

124
00:08:01,610 --> 00:08:03,331
but it's pretty scientific.

125
00:08:03,371 --> 00:08:05,613
They're like fraternal twins, if you think about it that way.

126
00:08:06,374 --> 00:08:08,456
It's definitely the most popular genre in the last 50 years.

127
00:08:10,572 --> 00:08:13,213
But there's no such thing as a neutral typeface, though.

128
00:08:13,554 --> 00:08:14,694
I wanted to emphasize that.

129
00:08:15,715 --> 00:08:16,856
There's only common ones.

130
00:08:17,116 --> 00:08:20,458
So these feel neutral because we see them so often.

131
00:08:20,718 --> 00:08:22,119
They kind of disappear.

132
00:08:22,620 --> 00:08:23,720
Because they're so common.

133
00:08:24,141 --> 00:08:26,582
Not because they are inherently neutral.

134
00:08:28,584 --> 00:08:32,846
So everything, no matter how plain it seems,

135
00:08:32,987 --> 00:08:34,648
carries some connotation with it.

136
00:08:36,031 --> 00:08:41,252
A humanist sans serif kind of has a little bit more handwriting influence to the shapes,

137
00:08:41,472 --> 00:08:46,294
less mechanical, and they're very popular with corporations and branding because they

138
00:08:46,334 --> 00:08:51,795
look clean and efficient and friendly, something like Gil Sans or Myriad, for example.

139
00:08:53,495 --> 00:08:58,377
Geometric sans are, you know, as they're described, geometric.

140
00:08:58,637 --> 00:09:04,498
They can be very elegant or futuristic, and there's also a pretty wide range of geometric

141
00:09:04,578 --> 00:09:04,918
moods.

142
00:09:07,241 --> 00:09:11,202
Square Sans is futuristic and mechanical too, like, you know,

143
00:09:11,282 --> 00:09:15,143
Bank Gothic on Call of Duty and movie posters,

144
00:09:15,203 --> 00:09:16,624
a typeface like Giro Style.

145
00:09:18,284 --> 00:09:21,425
Very popular on cars, as we'll see later.

146
00:09:22,786 --> 00:09:24,766
Serif... oops, I'm sorry.

147
00:09:25,006 --> 00:09:26,307
Serif typefaces have their own...

148
00:09:28,188 --> 00:09:30,048
their own serious and bookish look,

149
00:09:30,308 --> 00:09:32,209
or, you know, when used in games, historical.

150
00:09:33,406 --> 00:09:36,607
or classical Final Fantasy, for example, it feels cinematic.

151
00:09:38,568 --> 00:09:42,030
Or a newer game, 1886, The Order, has a very bookish

152
00:09:42,650 --> 00:09:45,231
and cinematic feel, too, with the use of serifs.

153
00:09:46,032 --> 00:09:51,274
And slab serifs on the bottom there are, of course, popular with cowboys and sports.

154
00:09:53,364 --> 00:09:56,266
Script typefaces, again, have a bunch of their own subgenres,

155
00:09:56,306 --> 00:09:58,347
and there's a pretty big variety of those, too.

156
00:09:59,849 --> 00:10:02,230
But they can look luxurious or formal,

157
00:10:02,551 --> 00:10:04,472
or very informal, like handwriting.

158
00:10:05,933 --> 00:10:08,655
Most commonly in the game world is casual scripts

159
00:10:08,755 --> 00:10:11,537
and really comic book lettering styles.

160
00:10:12,098 --> 00:10:12,678
Very popular.

161
00:10:13,459 --> 00:10:18,142
But typefaces can help set the mood and the tone of voice.

162
00:10:18,763 --> 00:10:20,464
But they can also be very flexible

163
00:10:20,944 --> 00:10:22,846
depending on the content and the context.

164
00:10:24,227 --> 00:10:27,629
But it really breaks down to these formal qualities and also stereotypes.

165
00:10:28,750 --> 00:10:32,613
And these stereotypes are developed over a long period of time

166
00:10:33,994 --> 00:10:36,076
because they get used over and over again.

167
00:10:37,117 --> 00:10:43,221
So this looks sci-fi because we've seen those type styles used in so many sci-fi things.

168
00:10:43,241 --> 00:10:44,943
It's okay. It makes sense.

169
00:10:45,622 --> 00:10:47,442
It's not a bad thing. It's just a thing.

170
00:10:48,702 --> 00:10:51,023
Lord of the Rings, kind of this fantasy style

171
00:10:51,363 --> 00:10:53,824
with a calligraphy called Unchill.

172
00:10:55,944 --> 00:10:58,845
And we see these typographic stereotypes everywhere.

173
00:10:59,345 --> 00:11:01,606
Not just games. Right. Police cars.

174
00:11:04,007 --> 00:11:05,927
A pizza place. Right.

175
00:11:07,108 --> 00:11:07,648
Or whipped cream.

176
00:11:10,397 --> 00:11:12,918
You know, these stereotypes act as a visual shortcut

177
00:11:12,958 --> 00:11:15,879
for our memory, and we recognize patterns.

178
00:11:16,099 --> 00:11:18,880
So we're able to guess the content based on the typography,

179
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:19,980
or at least get a clue.

180
00:11:20,580 --> 00:11:22,821
So this is essential graphic design.

181
00:11:23,101 --> 00:11:25,361
This is communicating an idea visually.

182
00:11:25,942 --> 00:11:27,142
That's what typefaces are good at.

183
00:11:28,442 --> 00:11:30,243
So, uh, see what I did there?

184
00:11:33,467 --> 00:11:41,393
Tiny Wings is a, a simple game. And the menu is pretty atmospheric, but the type style

185
00:11:41,453 --> 00:11:47,698
is a perfect match for the character and the style of the game. Right? Round, soft, fluffy.

186
00:11:49,580 --> 00:11:54,864
This, along with the, the color and the music choices, gives this game a sophistication

187
00:11:55,004 --> 00:11:58,546
to an otherwise a simple mechanic. But they're just using one typeface.

